fields.differencestoTD: The main difference was for these providers: Grŵp Llandrillo Menai, Gower College Swansea, David Game College Ltd, Grŵp NPTC Group. These are actually FE Colleges, but they are in the main collection (51). So although we call the dataset 'HEIs only', to match TDS we include these as well, otherwise there is nowhere to put FECs. FECs have been added to the main view the OU renamed. David Game College is an FEC in Collection 54, so TDS treats as AP. University of Buckingham is an AP in Collection 51, so TDS treats as HEI. A rule has been included to handle these exceptions and align to TDS. TDS has LAMDA, RADA, and CDD in as separate providers but they all recently merged so we show them all as CDD - we have left this as is. LAMDA and RADA are in separately, just as APs not HEIs, even though its in collection 51. So exception rules used for LAMDA/RADA

fields.differencestoTD: Nationality (Full) matches with same caveat that applies to Domicile (Country) in that the country name includes alternate name in square brackets in TD, whereas in TDSA we use the DW current label which is just the standard country name. There are also a few other, fairly minor, differences:TDSA: Guernsey and Jersey are grouped as Channel Islands, just as in Domicile Country. TD keeps these split even though they are grouped in Domicile Country“Czechoslovakia not otherwise specified” is classed as “non-EU” in TD but “EU” in TDSA. Probably an error in the TD metadata table as pre-split CZ was still an EU member.“Stateless” is classed as “Non-EU” in TDSA (reference) but “Unknown” in TD (51 meta-data). Possibly a classification change not reflected in the TD metadata table. After meeting with DW differences between Naionality and Countries intentional as need to be different under somecircumstances. Can contact Data Managment team if we need to justify naming conventions to customers or to get names changed. For TDSA we are happy to go with whatever the current convention is for now.
